    <div class="container">
      <h2>Central Heating in Liverpool's Victorian and Period Properties</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Liverpool has one of the highest concentrations of Victorian and Edwardian housing in England. Central heating installation in these properties requires specific knowledge and experience.</p>

      <div class="pf-card pf-card-navy" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <h3>What Makes Liverpool's Older Properties Different</h3>
        <p>Victorian and Edwardian terraces, Georgian townhouses and Edwardian semis in areas including Aigburth, Allerton, Sefton Park, Mossley Hill, Crosby and Woolton present specific challenges for central heating installation. Solid brick walls without cavities, limited access beneath suspended timber floors, chimney breasts used as flue routes and non-standard room proportions all affect how pipework must be routed.</p>
        <p>An installer without specific Liverpool experience can underestimate the complexity of these installations and either quote incorrectly or route pipework in ways that damage period features unnecessarily. Our engineers have been working in Liverpool's Victorian and Edwardian housing stock since the 1990s. We plan every pipe route to preserve original features where possible and to minimise visible pipework throughout.</p>
        <p>For properties with solid walls where standard pipe boxing would be intrusive, we discuss alternative routing options at the survey. We never cut corners that would affect the long-term performance of your system or damage features that cannot be easily restored.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="pf-card pf-card-orange" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <h3>First-Time Central Heating in a Liverpool Property</h3>
        <p>If your Liverpool property has never had central heating, a full installation from £3,500 is one of the most transformative and financially sound home improvements you can make. A property with no central heating is at a significant disadvantage in the Liverpool sales and rental market. A new system adds warmth, improves the EPC rating, satisfies buyer expectations and can add considerably more than its cost to the property value.</p>
        <p>The <a href="https://www.energysavingtrust.org.uk/advice/boilers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Energy Saving Trust</a> identifies central heating installation as one of the highest-impact improvements available for improving a property's energy efficiency and reducing annual heating costs. We carry out free surveys for homeowners considering installation before sale or rental.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

